| [[هند]] ||۱۲۵٬۳۴۴٬۷۳۶||۱۲٪||۲۲۶٬۴۴۹||برای ۸۶٬۱۲۵٬۲۲۱ نفر ''زبان دوم''.{{سخ}}برای ۳۸٬۹۹۳٬۰۶۶ نفر ''زبان سوم''||۱٬۰۲۸٬۷۳۷٬۴۳۶||<small>در بر دارندهٔ کسانی که انگلیسی ''زبان دوم'' آن‌ها است و کسانی که ''زبان سوم'' آن‌ها است. مربوط به سال ۲۰۰۱.<ref>Table C-17: Population by Bilingualism and trilingualism, 2001 Census of India [http://censusindia.gov.in/Tables_Published/C-Series/C-Series_link/C17_Bill_Tril.pdf]</ref><ref>Tropf, Herbert S. 2004.
[http://www.lilaproject.org/docs/India%20and%20its%20Languages%20v1.0.pdf India and its Languages]{{dead link|date=October 2010}}. Siemens AG, Munich</ref> همچنین این داده‌ها مربوط به کسانی است که تنها انگلیسی را ''صحبت'' می‌کنند ولی با آن ''کار'' نمی‌کنند.<ref>For the distinction between "English Speakers" and "English Users", see: TESOL-India (Teachers of English to Speakers of Other Languages). Their article explains the difference between the 350&nbsp;million number mentioned in a previous version of this Wikipedia article and a more plausible 90&nbsp;million number: {{bquote|Wikipedia's India estimate of 350&nbsp;million includes two categories – "English Speakers" and "English Users". The distinction between the Speakers and Users is that Users only know how to read English words while Speakers know how to read English, understand spoken English as well as form their own sentences to converse in English. The distinction becomes clear when you consider the China numbers. China has over 200~350&nbsp;million users that can read English words but, as anyone can see on the streets of China, only handful of million who are English speakers.}}</ref>
