| {{IPAlink|u:}} || b{{bold dark red|oo}}ed<ref group="vn" name="n7">The letter <''U''> can represent either {{IPA|/u:/}} or the [[iotation|iotated]] vowel {{IPA|/ju:/}}. In BRP, if this iotated vowel {{IPA|/ju:/}} occurs after {{IPA|/t/}}, {{IPA|/d/}}, {{IPA|/s/}} or {{IPA|/z/}}, it often triggers palatalisation of the preceding consonant, turning it to {{IPA|[t͡ɕ]}}, {{IPA|[d͡ʑ]}}, {{IPA|[ɕ]}} and {{IPA|[ʑ]}} respectively, as in ''tune'', ''during'', ''sugar'', and ''azure''. In American English, palatalisation does not generally happen unless the {{IPA|/ju:/}} is followed by ''r'', with the result that {{IPA|/(t, d, s, z)ju:r/}} turn to {{IPA|[tʃər]}}, {{IPA|[dʒər]}}, {{IPA|[ʃər]}} and {{IPA|[ʒər]}} respectively, as in ''nature'', ''verdure'', ''sure'', and ''treasure''.</ref>
